Some refactoring work.Remoed alot of code before starting to add more. Trimmed as much asnpossible to get to the point that I understood what was going on in eachnplace.nnSplit the server code into multiple objects to help my sanity. Arbiternis now the main class in the master process that keeps track of childnprocesses and so on and such forth.nnThe Worker class is responsible for handling incoming requests from thenserver socket passed to its constructor.n

Readd HTTP request processing.I based this on the BaseHTTPServer request handler class because I hadnissues with the other request handler. This one is having issues as wellnso I should go back to Benoit's but I'm starting to slide towards sleep.n

Be more considerate to future me.Sergey points out that its more proper to |= with the current value ofnthe fd flags. I concur.n

Be explicit about blocking status.Apparently the assumption that sockets don't inherit their blockingnstatus from the server socket is invalid. Or python sets the flagsnto match. Either way, we need clients to use blocking sockets sonwe're now explicitly setting the blocking status.n

Create an application abstraction.Groundwork for providing a post-fork app import option.nFixes paster's ini not being able to register changes.n

Major refactor of the configuration mechanics.* All configuration and bootup is handled by the Application objects.nn* There is now a strict ordering on the precedence of configurationnsettings:nn  1. Each option is given a default value of some sort in options.ininn  2. Any detectable framework configuration settings override the hardn coded defaults for options. Currently, only Paster applicationsn have support for this.nn  3. Anything that is specified in a Gunicorn configuration file (byn default gunicorn.conf.py) overrides what was possibly set by an framework specific configuration source.nn  4. Anything specified on the command line reins supreme. The commandn line is the final authority on a given configuration option.n Though, not all configuration options are available via commandn line.nn* Configuration metadata is pulled from an options.ini. In the future I'llnuse this to build the example gunicorn.conf.py and the config.rst filenin docs/site/config.rst.nnI haven't tested the differences thoroughly. The next item on my agendanis to figure out a way to start testing Gunicorn that doesn't make myneyes bleed.n

Avoid infinite loops spawning workers.I noticed with preload that if a worker fails to boot the arbiter willndutifully respawn it. Only to watch it die again. This patch makes it sonif a worker process exits before making it to the run loop the processnwill exit with a special exit code. When the arbiter sees this flag itnwill shutdown all processes assuming there is an unrecoverable error.n

check if Request Line is too large.You can now pass the parameter --limit-request-line or set thenlimit_request_line in your configuration file to set the max size of thenrequest line in bytes.nnThis parameter is used to limit the allowed size of a client's HTTPnrequest-line. Since the request-line consists of the HTTP method, URI,nand protocol version, this directive places a restriction on the lengthnof a request-URI allowed for a request on the server. A server needsnthis value to be large enough to hold any of its resource names,nincluding any information that might be passed in the query part of anGET request. By default this value is 4094 and can't be larger thann8190.nnThis parameter can be used to prevent any DDOS attack.n

test number of headers fields and size.Add --limit-request-fields (limit_request_fields) andn--limit-request-field-size (limit-request-field-size) options.nn- limit_request_fields:nnValue is a number from 0 (unlimited) to 32768. This parameter isnused to limit the number of headers in a request to prevent DDOSnattack. Used with the `limit_request_field_size` it allows morensafety.nn- limit_request_field_size:nnValue is a number from 0 (unlimited) to 8190. to set the limitnon the allowed size of an HTTP request header field.n

fix multiple issues with request limitpatch from Djoume Salvetti . address the following issues in gunicorn:nn* Gunicorn does not limit the size of a request header (then* limit_request_field_size configuration parameter is not used)nn* When the configured request limit is lower than its maximum value, then* maximum value is used instead. For instance if limit_request_line isn* set to 1024, gunicorn will only limit the request line to 4096 charsn* (this issue also affects limit_request_fields)nn* Request limits are not limited to their maximum authorized values. Forn* instance it is possible to set limit_request_line to 64K (this issuen* also affects limit_request_fields)nn* Setting limit_request_fields and limit_request_field_size to 0 doesn* not make them unlimited. The following patch allows limit_request_linen* and limit_request_field_size to be unlimited. limit_request_fields cann* no longer be unlimited (I can't imagine 32K fields to not be enoughn* but I have a use case where 8K for the request line is not enough).nn* Parsing errors (premature client disconnection) are not reportednn* When request line limit is exceeded the configured value is reportedn* instead of the effective value.n

fix gevent graceful timeout for real`server.kill()` is too aggressive. It sends a GreenletExit exceptionnto all the pool workers, causing them to exit immediately.nnA simple one line fix is to use `server.stop()`. In my testing, itnappears that `server.stop_accepting()` will make the server stopnlistening, but pending connections already in the `accept()` backlognare still handled. With `server.stop()` the accept backlog is notnhandled, the listener is closed in the worker, but existing requestsnare allowed to exit gracefully.n

Consistently get CWD across apps and arbiter.The Arbiter is smart about getting the CWD; first it checks the CWDnenvironment (which doesn't resolve symlinks), then it falls back to thenpython os.getcwd() (which does resolve symlinks). However, the Arbiternis the only place that does this, which will then do the right thingnwhen we reexec. However, when reloading the Arbiter, it won't pick upnchanges if the symlink has changed.nnBy changing the *app.py entry points to also use the same method forndetermining the CWD, we'll insert a symlink path into the first locationnin sys.path. Then our reloaded app will correctly pull in any newnchanges.n

Run worker's setup early than set num_workers`cfg.worker_class` is a property, which calls the classmethod `setup` ofnthe worker class when accessed.  Gevent worker relies on this mechanismnto call `gevent.monkey.patch_all()`.nnHowever, `num_workers` is a hooked property, when it is set, gunicornnwill call hook defined by user.  If the hooked code relies onngevent's monkey patch, it will fail because the monkey patch has notnbeen applied yet.nnThis commit makes sure that `worker_class` property getter invokesnbefore `num_workers` setter to resolve this problem.n

fix the correct remote addressThe remote address should return the direct client addr not a forwardednheader.nnThis is a breaking change. Added extra valid request (099) and test (send_special_chunks).``send_special_chunks`` sends the request data in two chunks, one having a length of 1 byte, which ensures there is no CRLF, and a second chunk containing the rest of the request data. Practically, this forces ``gunicorn.http.message.Request.read_line()`` to get the full request data with two buffer reads and reveal possible bugs related to the internal buffer mechanism. See #670 for more information.n

dont' override SERVER_* by the Host headerGunicorn shouln't override the SERVER_* by the Host header. Remove incompatible SSL option in Python 2.6An exposed SSL option, `ciphers`, was added in Python 2.7 and breaks oldernversions of Python with an unexpected kwargs error.nnI'm not sure if this is the best way to fix this, and I'm happy to considernother approachs. Some things I'm a bit up in the air about are:nn  i) This is only broken for Python 2.6 and older whose ssl module doesn'tn  expose this. Do the other types of workers not use ssl module, and thus mightn  be able to make use of the `cipher` kwarg?nn  ii) Should we silently or explicity fail? I couldn't find a nice way to don  this because the configuration setting has a default value and resulted inn  stringy code to special case the one setting`.nnWhat I would really like to do would add a python_version validator thatncould intelligently handle this, but I went off into the weeds figuring outnhow the SettingsMeta class works. :)n

Fix mixed up worker signal handlingCommit 81241907ffcf94517ffa14b8427205906b61b540 changed the signalnhandling by switching the roles of `TERM` and `QUIT` for the arbiternso that `TERM` is graceful and `QUIT` is not.nnAt the time, workers performed graceful shutdown on `QUIT` and quicknshutdown on `TERM` and `INT`. This behavior was also changed so thatn`QUIT` (and `INT`) cause a quick shutdown and `TERM` is graceful.nnHowever, the documentation incorrectly reversed the roles of the workernsignals and the arbiter was not updated to use the correct signals.nnThis commit fixes the documentation and the arbiter signals.n

Let the reloader kill the worker by signal onlyThere is no reason to raise a `SystemExit` because the reloader threadnwill die when the worker exits anyway. Having this exception can causentracebacks during interpreter shutdown (#910).nnClose #910n

stop to accept more requests when maximum accepted is achievedthis change makes sure that a worker don't handle more requests than it cannachieved.  The new workflow is quite more simple:nnlisteners are put in the poller. On read we try to accept on them.nWhen a connection is accepted it is put in the execution queuenWhen a request is done and the socket can be kept alived, we put it in thenpoller, on read event we will try to handle the new request. If it is not putnout of the poller before the keepalive timeout the socket will be closed.nif all threads are busy we are waiting until one request complet. If itndoesn't complete before the timeout we kill the worker.nnfix #908n
make sure we can alwas accept connection.This is done by limiting the number of kept alived requests to MAX WORKERnCONNECTIONS - N Threads so at any time we can accept N connection.n

Simplify sendfile logicA safe and reliable check for whether a file descriptor supports mmapnis to directly check if it is seekable. However, some seekable filendescriptors may also report a zero size when calling fstat. If therenis no content length specified for the response and it cannot bendetermined from the file descriptor then it is not possible to knownwhat chunk size to send to the client. In this case, is it necessarynto fall back to unwinding the body by iteration.nnThe above conditions together reveal a straightforward and reliablenway to check for sendfile support. This patch modifies the Responsenclass to assert these conditions using a try/catch block as part ofna new, simplified sendfile method. This method returns False if itnis not possible to serve the response using sendfile. Otherwise, itnserves the response and returns True. By returning False when SSL isnin use, the code is made even simpler by removing the special supportnfor SSL, which is served well enough by the iteration protocol.nnFix #1038n

[arbiter] close sockets on shutdownClose all the listeners when the arbiter shuts down. By doing so,nworkers can close the socket at the beginning of a graceful shutndown thereby informing the operating system that the socket cannbe cleaned up. With this change, graceful exits with such workersnwill refuse new connections while draining, allowing load balancersnto respond more quickly and avoiding leaving connections danglingnin the listen backlog, unaccepted.nnRef #922n

[thread] close sockets at graceful shutdownThe run loop has to change slightly to support graceful shutdown.nThere is no way to interrupt a call to `futures.wait` so insteadnthe pattern, used by the async workers, is to sleep for only onensecond at the most. The poll is extended to a one second timeoutnto match.nnSince threads are preemptively scheduled, it's possible that thenlistener is closed when the request is actually handled. For thisnreason it is necessary to slightly refactor the TConn class to storenthe listening socket name. The name is checked once at the start ofnthe worker run loop.nnRef #922n

Fix leak of duplicate file descriptor for bound sockets.`socket.fromfd` does not close the original file descriptor, so we have to explicitly close it to avoid a leak.nnSee also:nhttp://bugs.python.org/issue10099n

Fix #1368 by adding InotifyReloader and 'use-inotify' configuration optionCurrently, '--reload' uses FS polling to find out when files havenchanged. For some time, the Linux kernel has had a feature calledninotify that allows applications to monitor for FS events withoutnpolling.nnThis commit adds a new 'use-inotify' configuration option that willncause gunicorn to use the new 'InotifyReloader' instead of the defaultn'Reloader' when 'reload' is enabled.nnUsing inotify can result in lower CPU consumption by gunicorn especiallynwhen working with virtualized filesystems or environments with a largennumber of watched files / directories.n

Modify 'reload' config to be more consistent with existing API--reload = Runs the reloader with inotify if available and falls back onn   FS polling.n--reload=inotify = Forces the reloader to run with inotifyn--reload=poll = Forces the reloader to use FS pollingn

documentation: update systemd deploy unit examples (#1950)There's no need for PIDFile=, especially not for Type=notify services.rnsystemd knows the correct pid of the process it manages.rnrnNo need for the `--bind` option either, since gunicorn supports thernLISTEN_FDS environment variable and will use all of the sockets that systemdrnprovides. This way, it's also more flexible, since we can specify severalrnsockets in a .socket unit.rnrnThe .socket unit should specify User=www-data so that nginx can connect to the socket.rnThe service (gunicorn process) will inherit the file descriptor so itrndoesn't even need permissions for the socket (it's nginx which needsrnpermissions).rnrntmpfiles.d is not needed.rnrnreplace ExecStop=/bin/kill with KillMode=mixed

Avoid unnecessary chown of temporary filesWhen Gunicorn is configured to change the effective user or group of thenworker processes, it changes the owner and group fo the the temporarynfiles used for interprocess communication.nnWith this change, Gunicorn does not change the owner or group of thenfiles if the worker processes will run as the current effective user andngorup. This change avoids calling chown when it is not necessary, whichnmay allow Gunicorn to be used in environments that restrict use of thenchown syscall.nnRelates to #2059.n

socketfromfd: fix cross platform usageon osx and maybe some other systems, SO_PROTOCOL is not set, alsonthe socket family is not detected correctly.nnThis patch remove default values in socketfromfd and do the following:n* detect proper family using getsockname instead of getsocktoptn* if no type is given, default to SOCK_STREAM (we don't have any other type)n* if no protocol is given, default to 0 and let the system take care of it.n
